This seems like a problem, and something we should disallow.  ie, you should not be allowed to remove yourself from the Redfish privilege group, as that could lead to unintentionally DOS.

How is this different than us allowing HTTP to be disabled?
What if I want an IPMI only user? 
We allowed this in the D-Bus REST API (still allow that if you have it enabled).. I am struggling a bit with, we should always keep redfish in the user group.

> How is this different than us allowing HTTP to be disabled?

It's not, that should be disallowed as well (which I thought we did, maybe we something changed?).

> What if I want an IPMI only user?

Totally fine, so long as that IPMI user is not the one you're logged in as over redfish.  If you want yourself to become an ipmi only user, you should be making that change over IPMI, to ensure that there's still a working path to get into the system.
 
> We allowed this in the D-Bus REST API (still allow that if you have it enabled).. I am struggling a bit with, we should always keep redfish in the user group.

I don't think it's "always" only if you're logging in over Redfish, and trying to make modifications to your user.  Changing other users to be IPMI only is totally reasonable.

Considering that you've explicitly called out differences in behavior for various privilege levels, a single curl command doesn't seem like enough to test this.

Please also test that when changing a users privilege, that the expected behaviors are locked out.  IE, when you remove the IPMI privilege, you should be testing that ipmitool now fails to login.  When you remove ManagerConsole, ssh should now fail to login.
Does accountservice need to be updated to support the SupportedAccountTypes property now that this is patchable?  That seems important for a client to be able to know.
Has comments in the code that need addressed
Please write a method for converting redfish enums to dbus enums, using the if/else if ladder we use elsewhere.
This is the wrong error message.  The property value is in the list of allowed.
Abstract this to its own method.
Is this perfect if not then please suggest me error type?
Please don't add extra white space, it makes reviewing harder and makes the commit history/blame not as clean
it was not there So I add that sorry, I had to added that in first commit
no need for a variable for this.  When this occurs, just call return false at the site.
I've said before, we need to break this dependency to properly implement the CRUD interface.  These should be settable independently according to redfish.

This change is setting:
{"StrictAccountTypes", true}} and by StrictAccountTypes being true, this code is correct. 

Note we could set StrictAccountTypes to false this would be the more user friendly way to do this but I would say "StrictAccountTypes" = true is the more secure way. StrictAccountTypes is readwrite so we could also allow the user to set that value but I think for this first change, let's just make it ReadOnly and choose a value.  


                "StrictAccountTypes": {
                    "description": "Indicates if the service needs to use the account types exactly as specified when the account is created or updated.",
                    "longDescription": "This property shall indicate if the service needs to use the value of AccountTypes and OEMAccountTypes values exactly as specified.  A `true` value shall indicate the service needs to either accept the value without changes or reject the request.  A `false` value shall indicate the service may add additional `AccountTypes` and `OEMAccountTypes` values as needed to support limitations it has in separately controlling access to individual services.  If this property is not present, the value shall be assumed to be `false`.  An update of the service can cause account types to be added to or removed from the AccountTypes and OEMAccountTypes properties, regardless of the value of this property.  After a service update, clients should inspect all accounts where the value of this property is `true` and perform maintenance as needed.",
                    "readonly": false,
                    "type": [
                        "boolean",
                        "null"
                    ],
                    "versionAdded": "v1_7_0"
                },


and AccountTypes actually calls this out 

                "AccountTypes": {
....
                    "longDescription": "This property shall contain an array of the various manager services that the account is allowed to access.  This shall not include functionality for receiving events or other notifications.  If this property is not provided by the client, the default value shall be an array that contains the value `Redfish`.  The service may add additional values when this property is set or updated if allowed by the value of the StrictAccountTypes property.",
Some of this needs to be in the commit msg.

Agreed..... Lots of this detail needs to be in the commit message, it would help this patchset move forward.  For example, I was totally unaware of the language above.  Some things about the above that I see:

"A `true` value shall indicate the service needs to either accept the value without changes or reject the request."

It looks like the logic does that properly, agreed, but it also looks like the intent is that this property is settable by the user?

>"readonly": false,

So maybe we missed something in the intent there on implementation?



> The service may add additional values when this property is set or updated if allowed by the value of the StrictAccountTypes property.

It doesn't look like that's the behavior this code has.  Right now it just outright rejects the request.  If I'm reading the above right, if we wanted to do this, I think we need more logic around the StrictAccountTypes parameter?

IMO, it seems a lot easier to just break the permissions into two groups, but I'm not going to dictate which one gets worked on, I'll accept either.

(wouldn't it be nice if redfish had a test harness for stuff like this.....?)

There's no need to split these into two different sections.  just call your emplace_back calls in your conditionals on line 163.  That will delete most of your variables and simplify this code considerably.
You don't use "it" in this context, there's no need to assign it to a variable, especially in the conditional, just compare it directly against accountType->cend() without the intermediate.
Please do the "is this user trying to disable itself" check in another routine.

getUserGroupFromAccountType 
in this method, we have already set errors based on what we found in AccountType JSON data.
In that method, we are setting two errors.
1) propertyValueNotInList
2) strictAccountTypes

that is why here we don't have any error set
Can this return any errors that we would expect?  User account disabled?  something like that?
Do we have an error message which describes the account disable or something like that?

If the account say 'abc' is disabled, we get "Unauthorized" message when the account, 'abc',  tries to Set/Get AccountTypes. This I believe is expected.

However, another user with admin privilege can set AccountTypes to 'abc' even when the 'abc' is disabled

It is probably hard to say when or under what condition the Set fails. Have seen throwing InternalError for Set related async method calls in other areas.

Anything to do here to address this issue - other than resolving merge conflict?
Please don't use terinary operators for what is already a boolean statement.
Does it make sense to split this out to a separate change?
I would have been fine with you doing it here where you use it but since you broke it out I'm good with that too.
